[PlyCount "5"]

{Welcome to my 5th Chessable course! My previous course was a White repertoire
against the Pirc, Modern, and Philidor Defenses. That had been my most
ambitious project to date, where I demonstrated how White can get an advantage
against these hypermodern defenses with the Austrian Attack. This required a
tremendous amount of analytical work. However, trying to find an advantage
against the Caro-Kann proved to be an even tougher task. Not only is the
Caro-Kann a first-rate defense against 1.e4, but it is also extremely solid. I
know how hard is to find anything with White since I've also played it
extensively with the Black pieces. On top of that, I wanted to recommend a
practical repertoire that contained less than 100 theoretical trainable
variations. After months of research, I am happy to report that the course you
are now reading is not only a practical but also a very ambitious repertoire
against the Caro. It’s based on the Two Knights variation and inspired by
the games of Maxime-Vachier Lagrave, who has racked up an impressive number of
wins against the world’s elite with this system. I spent countless hours
refining this system with the latest versions of the revolutionary neural
network engines, Leela and Stockfish 12, running on very powerful cloud
computers. This resulted in significant improvements over current theory and
dozens of novelties. I would even go as far as to say that the Two Knights
variation is currently White’s best chance of getting an edge against the
Caro-Kann. As in all of my courses, I have tried to remain as objective as
possible in this repertoire and have clearly pointed out the lines in which
Black is able to equalize. My hope is that this repertoire is also useful for
Caro-Kann defense players with the black pieces. The good news is that there
are only 3 lines where Black is objectively equal and, even there, White’s
position is easier to play.} 1. e4 c6 2. Nc3 d5 3. Nf3 {This is known as the
Two-Knights variation of the Caro-Kann for rather obvious reasons. In this
variation, White delays or sometimes even omits d2-d4, prioritizing quick
piece development and maintaining a great degree of flexibility. We start by
covering Black's third move sidelines such as 3...d4 and 3...g6 in chapter 2.
None of these moves come anywhere close to equalizing. Inchapter 3, we examine
3...Nf6 which used to be one of Black's most reliable responses. However,
White found a new improvement on move 9 which has placed this variation under
a cloud. 3...dxe4 4.Nxe4 Nf6 is the topic ofchapter 4. This variation has been
gaining in popularity. However, I found several improvements over the current
theory which give White very good chances for an advantage. In chapter 5, we
quickly find out why 3...Bg4 4.h3 4...Bh5 is no longer played nowadays. White
can count on a clear advantage in this variation. The absolute mainline 3...
Bg4 4.h3 Bxf3 is one of Black's most reliable systems and was GM Erwin L'ami's
choice in his Lifetime Repertoire. Inchapter 6, we discuss setups where Black
refrains from playing ...Nf6. The setups where Black plays ...Nf6 are then
tackled in chapter 7. Chapter 8 contains 10 extensively annotatedmodel games,
four of which by our hero in this variation - super GM Maxime Vachier Lagrave
or MVL for short. The course concludes with15 thematic tactical exercises from
recent games in the Two-Knights variation.} *

