{[%evp 0,14,29,37,62,62,62,36,103,40,21,36,87,2,67,53,55]} 1. e4 c6 2. Nc3 d5
3. Nf3 Bg4 (3... Nf6 4. e5 Ne4 5. Ne2 Qb6 6. d4 e6 7. Ng3 c5 8. Bd3 {
Surprisingly, this natural developing move was not covered by GM Daniel
Fernandez in 'The Modernized Caro-Kann' book and Chessable course.} Nxg3 {
This was recommended by GM Vidit Gujrathi in the Chessbase FritzTrainer 'The
Fashionable Caro-Kann', and in 'The Dynamic Caro-Kann' DVD by IM Alex Astaneh
Lopez. However, none of these authors covered White's strongest move} 9. fxg3 {
which gives the first player a clear advantage as detailed in the 7...c5 in
chapter 2.}) 4. h3 Bxf3 5. Qxf3 e6 6. Be2 {This move was brought into the
limelight by MVL and is White's best chance for an opening advantage. It is
not mentioned in IM Jovanka Houska's 'Opening Repertoire: The Caro-Kann' as at
the time this book was published, this move was not well known.} Bc5 (6... Nf6
7. O-O dxe4 {was recommended by GM Lars Schandorff in the book 'GM Repertoire:
the Caro-Kann' for Quality Chess. I show how White can emerge with a slight
advantage and longstanding pressure in the 7...dxe4 variation in chapter 6.} (
7... Bc5 {was recommended in 'Bologan's Caro-Kann: A Modern Repertoire for
Black' by GM Victor Bologan for NewInChess. However, he did not cover the
critical 9.Qf4! that places Black under serious pressure. The details can be
found in the 7...Bc5 in chapter 7.})) (6... Nd7 {was also recommended by GM
Victor Bologan in the aforementioned book. Aided by Leela, I found a novelty
on move 9 which gives White a slight advantage. Refer to the 6...Nd7 for the
details.}) 7. O-O Nd7 {was GM Erwin L'Ami's recommendation in the Chessable
course 'Lifetime Repertoire: the Caro-Kann'. Using Stockfish 12, I've come up
with a new approach that is not covered in Erwin's course and gives White a
slight advantage. The details can be found in the 6...Bc5 7...Nd7 in chapter 6.
} (7... Ne7 {was recommended by GM Francesco Rambaldi in the book 'The
Caro-Kann Revisited' for Thinkers Publishing. The specific clash occurs in the
6...Bc5 7...Ne7 in chapter 6. Black is objectively equal but White's position
is still easier to play in a practical game.}) *

