e4 g6 2.d4 Bg7 3.Nc3 c6 4.Nf3 d5. Black intends to fianchetto his dark-squared
bishop.} (3... a6 {White can easily gain the upper hand by expanding in the
center with} 4. d4 Bg4 5. h3 {Asking the bishop to make decision.} Bh5 (5...
Bxf3 {surrenders the bishop pair and after} 6. Qxf3 e6 {I recommend the simple
and rare} 7. Be2 {which gives White a slight advantage after} Nf6 8. O-O $146 {
This move is already a novelty which is a testament to how unexplored 3...a6
is. Well, it's unexplored for good reason. White can get a very pleasant
position and a slight advantage with the following set of natural moves:} dxe4
9. Nxe4 Nxe4 10. Qxe4 Be7 11. Rd1 $14 {White will continue with c2-c4 and Bf4
with a very pleasant position. White's extra space and the bishop pair grant
him a slight but stable, longterm advantage.}) 6. exd5 cxd5 {And now White
should chase Black's light-squared bishop with} 7. g4 Bg6 8. Ne5 e6 9. h4 {
Threatening to trap the bishop with h4-h5.} f6 10. Nxg6 {White picks up the
bishop pair and damages Black's pawn structure.} hxg6 11. Qd3 Kf7 12. Bd2 {
followed by O-O-O and Re1. Black's pawn structure is compromised and the king
on f7 is completely misplaced. White was clearly better and was able to
convert his advantage in 1-0 Ragger, Markus-Shengelia, Davit (2544), 2020.}) ({
Black can also go against everything a Caro-player believes in, that is lock
his light-square bishop with} 3... e6 {and enter a variation of the French
Defense a full tempo down!} 4. d4 Bb4 (4... Nf6 {isn't much better.} 5. e5 Nfd7
{transposes to the 4...Nfd7 in chapter 3.}) 5. e5 {And we've reached a
variation of the Winawer a full tempo down for Black since Black's c7-c6 makes
