soon follow with a slight advantage. White can also consider expanding on the
queenside with a4-a5 later on.}) 7. Bc4 {followed by O-O.} Ngf6 8. Nxf6+ Nxf6
9. O-O O-O 10. Re1 {White can continue with c2-c3 to reinforce the d4 pawn and
look to centralize his knight with Ne5. Qe2, Rad1, and Bf4 are also in the
cards. White has more space and better control over the center, granting the
first player a slight advantage.} *

