{Hitting the f7 pawn.} Nd8 17. Qg4 Bb5 {Black has finally realized his plan of
exchanging the light-squared bishops. However, in the meantime, White has
developed a strong initiative on the kingside.} 18. Bd2 {White has just
completed development. Rf2 followed by Raf1 are coming next with a clear
advantage. Black won't be able to hold on to the f7 pawn.}) 13. b4 {Let's now
see what happens if Black decides to keep his king in the center for the time
being.} O-O-O {We have been following the game Ter Sahakyan, S (2623)-Vogel, R
(2465) Chigorin Memorial 2019, where White played 14.b5. This game is
annotated in the model games chapter. Even stronger is to start with the novel
and prophylactic} (13... Be7 {This position was reached in Galperin, P. (2462)
-Rudolf, M. (2328) 2019, where White played 14.g4. Once again, it was better
to first play the prophylactic} 14. Kh1 {stepping out of the a7-g1 diagonal.}
a6 {White should now expand on the kingside with the thematic} 15. g4 {with
the idea g5 followed by Ng5 to attack the f7 pawn.} O-O-O {Black has committed
his king to the queenside. As such, White should now direct his attention to
this side of the board with} 16. Rb1 {intending to break open the b-file with
b4-b5. Notice how Black's ...a6 move has come back to bite him. This pawn only
helps White open the b-file.} Kb8 17. b5 {Blasting open the b-file.} axb5 18.
Bd2 {The b5 pawn is not going to run away so White develops his final minor
piece.} Qc7 19. Bxb5 {Bxc6 followed by Bb4 is now a big threat. Black would be
left with a terrible light-squared bishop vs White's strong knight and hence
no counterplay. White can then recoup the d4 pawn with Qd3 and Nxd4.
Conclusion: The 3...Nf6 variation was once a reliable weapon vs the Two
Knights. However, 9.fxg3 gives White a clear advantage and puts Black under
serious pressure. This is the reason why many Caro players have abandoned this
variation. And with the novelties I present in this chapter, I'm sure they
won't be coming back to it any time soon!}) 14. Kh1 {getting the king out of
the g1-a7 diagonal. Black's only active plan is to break in the center with ...
f6.} f6 15. Bf4 g5 ({Trying to close the kingside with} 15... f5 {is not a
