domination over the entire board.}) 11. bxc3 dxe4 12. Qxe4 Nf6 13. Qe2 {
White has the bishop pair and control over the center. Black is quite solid
but lacks an active plan. All in all, White is slightly better and is the only
one pushing. White can continue with a4 and c4 and then develop the
dark-squared bishop to d2 or g5.}) ({Attacking the d4-pawn with} 7... Qb6 {
has been played a few times.} 8. Qd3 $1 {is the easiest way of protecting the
d4-pawn.} dxe4 9. Nxe4 Ngf6 10. c3 Be7 11. O-O O-O 12. a4 $14 {with the idea
a5. Regrouping with Nd2-c4 is also on the agenda, with a slight but stable
advantage.}) (7... g6 8. Be3 {transposes to the 6...g6 variation.}) 8. Nxe4
Ngf6 {And here, Leela comes up with the interesting novelty} 9. Nd2 {keeping
as many pieces on the board. Black has less space so it makes sense to avoid
exchanges. This give White a slight advantage and was not covered by GM Victor
Bologan in the book 'Bologan's Caro-Kann: A Modern Repertoire for Black'.} Be7
10. O-O O-O 11. Nc4 {when White has a slight but long-lasting advantage thanks
to the extra space and the pair of bishops. White can continue with Rd1 and
then expand on the queenside with a2-a4-a5.} *

