1. e4 c6 2. Nc3 d5 3. Nf3 Bg4 4. h3 Bxf3 5. Qxf3 e6 6. Be2 {In the previous
chapter, we examine all of Black's setups without ...Nf6. Here, we're going to
focus exclusively on The only setup left to tackle is when Black develops his
knight to f6.} Nf6 7. O-O {Securing the king. White is now threatening to
expand in the center with d2-d4.} Bc5 {This is Black's best move, taking
control over the d4-square.} (7... Be7 {is too passive and simply allows White
to expand in the center.} 8. d4 dxe4 9. Qe3 {Protecting the d4-pawn. White
will recapture the pawn on e4 with Nxe4 on the next turn.} Nbd7 {And here, a
logical set of moves transpire:} 10. Nxe4 Nxe4 11. Qxe4 Nf6 12. Qd3 O-O 13. c3
{White has more space and the pair of bishops. Expanding on the queenside with
a4-a5 is a natural plan. Black is nevertheless quite solid, which means White
only has a slight advantage albeit a long-lasting one.}) ({Liquidating the
center with} 7... dxe4 {fails to solve Black's problems.} 8. Nxe4 Nxe4 9. Qxe4
Nd7 {Heading to f6.} 10. d4 {Taking the center and opening up the dark-squared
bishop.} Nf6 11. Qd3 {This is a natural square for the queen, keeping an eye
on the d4 pawn. From d3, it can swing to either side of the board.} Bd6 {
However, White can slowly improve his position starting with} 12. a4 {followed
by a4-a5. White can then expand on the queenside with c2-c3 and b2-b4.
Similarly, g3+h4 to gain space on the kingside will slowly squeeze Black.
Black's position is very hard to play in practice since he lacks an active
plan. In fact, MVL easily defeated GM Agrest from this position in 2017 in a
model game which is annotated in the model games chapter.}) (7... d4 {This
advance is weaker than on move 6 since Black has already committed his knight
