the bishop with a tempo on Black's knight.} Nxg3 9. fxg3 {As we saw in chapter
2, this is recapture is much stronger than 9.hxg3.} cxd4 10. O-O Nc6 11. Qe2 {
Reinforcing the e5 pawn. White is now threatening Ng5 with a strong attack on
the f7 pawn.} Be7 {This move is a big mistake as it fails to address White's
threat. In fact, White can just go} 12. Ng5 {anyways.} Nxe5 {intending to meet}
13. Qxe5 {with} f6 {However, White can simply drop back with} 14. Qe2 fxg5 15.
Bxg5 {This is the point. White has Qh5+ and so he simply picks up the g5 pawn.
Black's position is now in tatters.} Bd7 {Black is trying to run away to the
queenside. However, we won't let that happen!} (15... Bxg5 16. Qh5+ Kd7 17.
Qxg5 $18 {is disastrous for Black.}) 16. Qh5+ g6 17. Bxg6+ {There goes another
pawn and this time with a check!} Kd8 18. Bf4 ({Also possible was} 18. Bxe7+
Kxe7 19. Bd3 $18 {followed by Rf7 with a completely winning position.}) 18...
Be8 19. Qe5 {Centralizing the queen and hitting the rook on h8.} Rf8 20. Bxh7 {
There goes yet another pawn. Black could have already resigned but decided to
keep playing for a few more moves.} Kd7 21. Bd3 Bf6 22. Qe2 Bg6 23. Bh6 Bxd3
24. cxd3 Rf7 {And now} 25. Qh5 {attacking the only defender of the bishop on
f6 wins on the spot.} Ke7 26. g4 {Black has no good way of meeting g4-g5 and
so he resigned. A fantastic game by GM Forcen, who completely demolished an IM
in only 26 moves. 1-0 (26) Forcen Esteban, D (2528)-Cruz Lledo, P (2432) Las
Palmas 2017} 1-0

