{[%evp 0,85,27,12,68,47,45,42,66,62,47,42,25,31,31,6,13,-5,-5,-25,-17,-25,-39,
-47,-49,-42,-4,-12,-16,-45,-45,-72,-66,-76,-27,-52,-38,-75,-20,-21,-10,-10,3,
-4,3,-4,66,41,54,16,66,-4,16,-10,10,18,6,23,34,30,124,92,83,0,187,252,215,74,
186,177,412,477,573,512,516,498,505,473,463,422,581,590,771,1045,1686,1357,
1686,2368] The following is another model game in the 3...Nf6 variation, this
time between the Armenian GM Samvel Sahakyan and German IM Roven Vogel.} 1. e4
c6 2. Nf3 d5 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. e5 Ne4 5. Ne2 {Preventing Black from playing ...
Nxc3, which would double our pawns.} Qb6 6. d4 e6 7. Ng3 {Clearing the way for
Bd3 to get rid of Black's knight.} c5 8. Bd3 Nxg3 9. fxg3 {As we saw in
chapter 2, this recapture away from the center is very strong.} Nc6 10. O-O
cxd4 11. Qe2 {Reinforcing the e5 pawn. White is now threatening Ng5 with a
strong attack on the f7 pawn.} h6 {Stopping Ng5.} 12. a3 {Preparing to expand
on the queenside with b2-b4.} Bd7 13. b4 O-O-O {This was all covered in 7...c5
in chapter 2, where I recommended the novel and prophylactic 14.Kh1, getting
the king out of the g1-a7 diagonal. This is an improvement over} 14. g4 {
which immediately starts active operations on the kingside. This is Black's
main problem in this variation. White can simply expand on both sides of the
board with b2-b4 and g3-g4-g5 while Black does not have an active plan.} Kb8
15. Bf4 {White develops his last minor piece and overprotects the e5 pawn.} Be7
16. Bg3 {White removes the bishop from f4, where it was blocking the f-file.
Additionally, the bishop can later drop back to f2 to attack the d4 pawn.} Ka8
17. Kh1 {Improving the king's position. Black has no counterplay and so White
can improve his position incrementally.} Rc8 18. Rae1 {It was stronger to
start with Bf2 as it's not clear where this rook belongs on e1.} Rhf8 19. Bf2 {
Hitting the d4 pawn. White is now threatening to pick up this pawn with b4-b5
followed by Bxd4.} f6 20. b5 {Removing Black's main defender of the d4-pawn.}
Na5 ({Stronger was} 20... Nxe5 $1 {with the point that} 21. Bxd4 {is strongly
met by} Nxd3 {sacrificing the queen but picking up two bishops and a rook.} 22.
Bxb6 Nxe1 23. Nd4 axb6 {when Black has two bishops and a rook for White's
queen. The position remains quite complicated but is objectively balanced.})
21. Bxd4 {White has now restored material equality and maintains all the
trumps in the position that is the extra space and more active pieces.} Bc5 22.
Bb2 {White naturally avoids piece exchanges since he has more space.} Nc4 23.
Bxc4 dxc4 24. a4 {Defending the b5 pawn.} a6 25. Bc3 ({Stronger was} 25. Rd1 $1
Rcd8 {and now} 26. Nd2 $18 {simply picks up the c4-pawn with a decisive
advantage.}) 25... f5 {Black is desperately trying to create some counterplay.
However, with only one rook on f8, he has no chances of creating any threats
against our king. White, on the other hand, will launch a strong attack
against Black's king with Ra1 and Rfb1 followed by the advance of the a- and
b-pawns.} 26. gxf5 Rxf5 27. Rd1 Be8 28. Ra1 {White now directs his pieces
against Black's king.} Kb8 29. Rfb1 {a4-a5 is coming next with a very strong
attack.} Bh5 30. a5 Qd8 31. Qe4 {This natural move is actually a big mistake.}
(31. bxa6 $1 {followed by Rxb7 was the way to go.}) 31... Be8 {And Black
returns the blunder.} ({The exchange sacrifice} 31... Rxf3 $3 {would have
turned the tables. The tactical justification is that} 32. gxf3 {is met by the
stunning} Qh4 $17 {he queen on h4 is taboo because of ...Bxf3#}) 32. bxa6 {
Prying open the b-file.} Bc6 33. Qe2 {Another mistake that could have allowed
Black back into the game.} ({Much stronger was} 33. Qxc4 $1 {when} Rxf3 {
loses to} 34. axb7 Bxb7 35. Rxb7+ $1 {Removing the defender of the rook on f3.
On} Kxb7 36. gxf3 Qd5 37. Qxd5+ exd5 $18 {White is three pawns up and thus
completely winning.}) 33... Rxf3 {A strong exchange sacrifice, which should
have kept Black in the game.} 34. gxf3 {But not} g5 {as this is simply too
slow.} (34... Qg5 {with the idea Rf8 was necessary.} 35. Rxb7+ Ka8 {when
Black's king is perfectly safe on a8.}) 35. axb7 {Crashing through. Black is
now toast.} Rc7 36. a6 {a6-a7 is now a big threat.} Ba7 37. Ba5 {Pinning and
winning!} g4 38. Bxc7+ Qxc7 39. Rf1 {Effectively parries Black's only threat.}
Qf7 40. Rad1 {Rd8 is now a big threat.} Bb6 41. Rd6 Bxf3+ 42. Rxf3 gxf3 43.
Rxb6 {A cute finish. Black is defenseless against a7+ followed by Qb8# and so
he resigned. 1-0 Ter Sahakyan, Samvel (2623)-Vogel, Roven Chigorin Memorial
27th St Petersburg 2019} 1-0

