{[%evp 0,95,29,12,68,52,51,42,42,42,42,30,19,11,9,-24,-16,-8,49,44,44,50,50,16,
41,38,40,32,35,32,35,44,51,51,66,71,77,65,85,36,24,15,14,3,16,8,29,4,-9,0,-2,
-9,-9,-37,9,-10,-1,4,36,52,52,52,46,53,63,65,63,70,63,62,63,65,69,63,69,63,63,
63,71,63,63,63,79,87,104,104,104,104,104,104,133,121,158,163,162,209,355,132]
The following is a model game in the 3...dxe4 4...Nf6 variation between the
German GM Jan Schroeder and the American IM Kevin Wang.} 1. e4 c6 2. Nc3 d5 3.
Nf3 dxe4 4. Nxe4 Nf6 5. Qe2 Bf5 {This continuation has been played by several
strong GMs, including the World Champion in 2017. However, theory has moved on
quite a bit since 2017 and GM Schroeder convincingly shows how White can get
an advantage.} 6. Nxf6+ {White compromises Black's pawn structure. Note that
the e-pawn is pinned.} gxf6 7. d3 {White covers the c2-pawn and opens up the
dark-squared bishop, all while restricting Black's bishop on f5.} Nd7 8. g3 {
Preparing to fianchetto the light-squared bishop and castle kingside.} Ne5 {
This is a clever move, aiming to exchange another pair of minor pieces and
enter an endgame, where Black's compromised pawn structure isn't such a big
factor.} 9. Nxe5 Qa5+ {This is the point. Black can recapture on e5 with the
queen thanks to this check.} 10. Bd2 Qxe5 11. Bc3 {This is stronger than
trading queens on e5, which was MVL's choice in the game ½-½ (48) Vachier
Lagrave, M (2783)-Carlsen, M (2851) Leuven 2017. White wants Black to be to
one to capture our queen which will automatically develop the e2 bishop. This
is a small detail but it makes the difference between equality and a slight
advantage.} Qxe2+ 12. Bxe2 h5 {Black wants to exchange off his weak and
isolated h-pawn. This was all covered in the course in the 5...Bf5 variation
in chapter 4, where I recommended the novel 13.h4 to fix Black's h-pawn, which
is more precise than the move played in the game.} 13. a4 {White expands on
the queenside and wants to continue with a4-a5 and then use the ROVER rook and
up over with Ra4-h4 to attack Black's pawn on h5.} O-O-O {This move is
inaccurate as it fails to counter White's plan.} ({Better was} 13... a5 {
to stop White from pushing ahead with a5 and activating his rook via a4.}) 14.
a5 a6 15. Ra4 {Here comes the ROVER, which is heading to h4 to attack Black's
weak and isolated pawn on h5.} Bg6 16. Rh4 Rh7 {Black's rook on h7 and the
bishop on g6 are tied down to the defense of the h5 pawn.} 17. O-O Rd7 18. Re1
f5 {This is a strategic mistake. Black blocks his own bishop on g6.} 19. Rc4 {
White moves the rook away from h4, clearing the way for h2-h4 to fix Black's
weak pawn on h5. Black has several weaknesses but at the moment he is doing a
good job of covering all of them. In these situations, White should improve
his position incrementally, that is place all of his pieces on the best
possible squares and try to grind Black down. Black has no active plan and
should sit tight and defend, which is hard to do in a practical game.} f6 20.
h4 e5 21. Bf1 {Now White improves the position of the light-squared bishop,
which is heading to h3 to attack the f5 pawn. White can then lift his rook on
e1 with Re3-f3, which should pick up this pawn.} Bd6 22. Bh3 Kc7 23. Bb4 {
Black has less space and so exchanging pieces is not the best idea. White,
however, has a concrete idea in mind. He wants to prepare the f2-f4 break.} ({
Stronger was} 23. Re3 {followed by Rf3, which would net White the f5 pawn.})
23... Bxb4 24. Rxb4 Rd5 {Black correctly activates his rook and targets the a5
pawn.} 25. Ra4 {White's rook is now very passive and Black's rook on d5 is now
active. We can clearly see that 23.Bb4 was not a good idea.} Rhd7 26. f4 Re7 {
This is a big mistake. The rook on e7 is very passive.} ({Much stronger was} 
26... Rc5 $1 {to attack the c2-pawn.} 27. Re2 Rdd5 $11 {when Black has zero
problems.}) 27. Kf2 Kd8 28. Re3 {As I mentioned before, it's hard to sit tight
in a position where you have no active plan. It was nevertheless necessary.
Black instead played} Rd4 {which blunders the game away.} ({It was much better
to attack the b2-pawn with} 28... Rb5 $1 29. b3 {followed by} c5 $14 {when
it's not so easy for White to make progress.}) 29. Rxd4+ exd4 30. Rxe7 Kxe7 31.
c3 {This is the problem. White transforms the pawn structure and creates a
passed d-pawn. This, combined with Black's weak pawns on f5 and h5, will
decide the game. A great example of the principle of two weaknesses.} dxc3 (
31... c5 {is the move that Black would like to play but he has no way to
defend the b7 pawn after} 32. Bg2 $18) 32. bxc3 Kd6 33. d4 Kd5 34. Bf1 {
cutting off Black's king.} Bf7 (34... c5 {is still not possible because of} 35.
Bg2+ {which picks up the b7 and a6 pawns, when White's own a-pawn will decide
the game.} Kc4 36. Bxb7 cxd4 37. Bxa6+ Kxc3 38. Bb7 d3 39. a6 d2 40. Bf3 $18 {
and the a-pawn queens.}) 35. Ke3 {White defends the d4-pawn. Bd3 followed by
c2-c4 will then kick Black's king back.} Kd6 36. Bd3 Be6 37. Be2 {White makes
a couple of moves, presumably getting closer to move 40 where the players
receive extra time.} Bf7 38. c4 {Enough messing around. White will now
transfer his king to b4.} Ke7 39. Kd3 Kd6 40. Kc3 Bg6 41. Bd3 Bh7 42. Kb4 Bg6
43. Bc2 Bh7 44. Bb3 {White is now ready to break in the center with c4-c5
followed by d4-d5.} Bg6 45. c5+ Kc7 46. Be6 Kd8 47. Kc4 Ke7 48. d5 {Black has
no defense against dxc6 followed by Bc8 and so he threw in the towel. If} Be8 {
then} (48... Kd8 {to stop Bc8 is also no good as it allows White to create a
protected passed pawn with} 49. d6 {which will decide the game. For example,}
Bh7 {drops to h5 pawn to} 50. Bf7 $18) 49. dxc6 bxc6 50. Bc8 $18 {wins the a6
pawn and the game. 1-0 Schroeder, Jan Cristian (2572)-Wang, Kevin (2427) Saint
Louis SPICE Cup 2019} 1-0

