{[%evp 0,47,29,17,68,45,51,42,42,42,38,16,34,26,36,23,24,14,14,8,-1,12,7,11,5,
-14,0,12,32,16,0,13,31,31,25,25,40,-1,40,104,90,92,110,117,130,115,139,139,161,
161] The following is another model game in the 3...dxe4 4...Nf6 variation
between Swedish GM Niels Grandelius (2681) and the Dutch IM Miguoel Admiraal 
(2510).} 1. e4 c6 2. Nf3 d5 3. Nc3 dxe4 4. Nxe4 Nf6 5. Qe2 Nxe4 6. Qxe4 Nd7 {
This is one of Black's best ways of meeting the Two Knights variation.} 7. d4 {
As I mentioned in chapter 4, the most common move is 7.Bc4 but Black is doing
well there. 7.d4 is much rarer and I believe is White's best chance for a
slight advantage.} Nf6 8. Qd3 g6 {Preparing to fianchetto the dark-squared
bishop. This move also gives Black the option of developing the bishop to f5.}
9. Be2 Bg7 10. O-O O-O {This was all covered in the 6...Nd7 in chapter 4,
where I recommended starting with 11.Re1, which is more flexible than} 11. c4 {
That being said, expanding in the center is not bad either.} Qc7 12. g3 {
An interesting idea. White slightly weakens the light-squares around his king
to develop the bishop to f4.} Bg4 13. Bf4 Qa5 14. Rfe1 {Simple chess, White
brings the rook to the half-open e-file.} Rad8 15. Qb3 Nh5 16. Be3 {White
drops the bishop back to safety and reinforces the d4-pawn.} Qc7 17. Rad1 {
Bringing the last piece into the game. Notice how White is perfectly
centralized and can now look to further activate his pieces with moves like
Ne5.} Rd7 18. Rd2 (18. h3 {was evens stronger, forcing Black to give up the
pair of bishops.} Bxf3 19. Bxf3 Nf6 20. d5 $16 {when Black is under serious
pressure.}) 18... Qa5 {This move is a big mistake as it exposes Black to the
following tactical sequence} 19. Ne5 Bxe5 20. Bxg4 {This is the point, White
is now attacking the rook on d7 so Black has no choice but to play} Rxd4 21.
Bxh5 Rxd2 22. Bxd2 Qxd2 {and now the bishop on e5 hangs at the end of the line}
23. Rxe5 gxh5 24. Qxb7 {Material is level but Black's pawn structure is
completely compromised and his king is very exposed. White has a decisive
advantage and Black decided to throw in the towel right away rather than see
White pick up a7, c6, and h5 pawns. A very nice game by Grandelius and a good
example of how powerful 7.d4 can be. White built a strong pawn center with c4
and d4, centralized all of his pieces and then won. Despite the blunder on
move 18, Black's position is much harder to play in a practical game as he has
less space and lacks an active plan. 1-0 (24) Grandelius, N (2681)-Admiraal, M
(2510) Budva 2019} 1-0

