{[%evp 0,75,29,11,74,42,42,38,70,61,102,102,83,105,91,81,85,62,40,33,33,27,25,
25,68,86,37,60,60,18,40,47,-1,-21,-21,35,60,10,-33,-11,-17,-59,-54,43,36,27,12,
21,46,48,54,58,77,69,91,92,134,134,242,284,301,301,301,237,237,275,401,378,329,
399,399,320,320,320,473,569,603,619] The following is a model game in the 3...
Bg4 4...Bh5 variation between GM Andrei Istratescu and GM Dmitry Svetushkin.} 
1. e4 c6 2. Nc3 d5 3. Nf3 Bg4 4. h3 Bh5 5. exd5 cxd5 6. Bb5+ Nc6 7. g4 Bg6 8.
Ne5 Rc8 9. d4 e6 10. Qe2 Bb4 11. h4 {White is now threatening to trap Black's
bishop with h4-h5.} Nge7 {And Black decides to sacrifice it for three pawns,
which is his only chance in this position.} 12. h5 Be4 13. f3 {There goes
Black's bishop, which is now trapped.} O-O 14. Nxc6 Nxc6 15. Be3 {Covering the
d4 pawn.} Qf6 {Black attacks the d4 and f3 pawns, initiating a forced sequence
of moves.} 16. fxe4 Nxd4 17. Bxd4 Qxd4 18. Rd1 {Bringing the rook into the
game with tempo.} Bxc3+ 19. bxc3 Qxc3+ 20. Kf1 dxe4 21. Qxe4 Qxc2 {This whole
sequence was practically forced. As I mentioned in the15...Qf6 in chapter 5,
White now has a pleasant choice:  1 Enter a two-results endgame with 22.Qxc2
or  2 Drop the queen back with 22.Qe2, which gives Black the option of keeping
the queens on.  However, Black's king will be extremely vulnerable. Option 2
is objectively stronger and my main recommendation. GM Istratescu in this game,
however, went for option 1} 22. Qxc2 {entering a two results endgame.} Rxc2 23.
a4 {If White manages to get Rh3-d3-d7 win, Black will be completely lost. Thus,
Black's only chance is to eliminate the queenside pawns with} a6 24. Be2 {
followed by} Ra2 {going after the a4 pawn.} 25. Rd7 {Going after the b7 pawn.}
Rxa4 26. Rxb7 h6 ({It was better to exchange a pair of rooks with} 26... Ra1+
27. Kg2 Rxh1 28. Kxh1 h6 29. Bxa6 {when it's not easy to make progress with
White.}) 27. Kf2 f5 {Black tries to exchange another pair of pawns and create
counterplay against White's king. However, he severely weakens the 7th rank
which will end up costing the game} 28. Rc1 {White immediately pounces on the
opportunity to double on the 7th rank.} Rf7 29. Rc8+ Rf8 30. Rcc7 {The g7 pawn
is about to drop when Black's king will be in a world of trouble.} fxg4+ 31.
Kg3 Ra3+ 32. Kg2 {White is now threatening mate in three with Rxg7, Rh7+ and
Rbg7#.} Rf4 33. Rxg7+ Kf8 34. Rgd7 {Threatening Rd8#.} Kg8 35. Bd3 {White's
bishop will now decide the game.} Ra2+ 36. Kg1 Raf2 37. Bc4 {A nice way to
finish the game.} Rxc4 38. Kxf2 {Black resigned as he is down an entire rook.
1-0 Istratescu, Andrei (2598)-Svetushkin, Dmitry (2461) Patras 2001} 1-0

