268,262,273,273,273,324,267,276,279,263,292,214,257,417,407] The following is
a model game in the 3...Bg4 4...Bh5 variation between the polish IM Szymon
Gumularz and the hungarian FM Levente Marosi.} 1. e4 c6 2. Nc3 d5 3. Nf3 Bg4 4.
h3 Bh5 5. exd5 {White opens up the a4-d8 diagonal, taking advantage of the
fact that Black's bishop on h5 is offside.} cxd5 6. Bb5+ Nc6 7. g4 Bg6 8. Ne5
Rc8 9. d4 e6 10. Qe2 {A very strong move, making it difficult for Black to
kick our knight on e5 with ...f6 since the e6 pawn would then hang.} Bd6 {
As mentioned in the 10...Bd6 variation in chapter 5, this seemingly natural
