threatening ...exd5 and ...Nxd4.} (12... Nge7 {isn't much better.} 13. Nxe7
Bxe7 14. c3 {Consolidating the extra pawn on d4. White is not afraid of} Qd5
15. Rf1 Rxh3 16. Be3 a6 17. Bc4 Qg2 18. O-O-O $16 {Black won his pawn back but
is still under serious pressure. White's bishop pair and strong center give
him a clear advantage.}) 13. Bxc6 {Simple and strong. White eliminates Black's
knight, neutralizing the threat of ...Nxd4.} Rxc6 14. Ne3 Nf6 15. c3 {White
has consolidated his extra pawn and intends to complete development with Qf3
and Bd2. Black does not sufficient compensation for the missing pawn.} Bf4 16.
Qf3 {Improving the position of the queen with a tempo on Black's bishop. From
f3, the queen defends the h3 pawn allowing White to castle short on the next
turn.} g5 17. O-O Nd7 18. b3 {This is innaccurate.} ({Stronger was} 18. Nc2 $16
{exchanging off the dark-squared bishops with a clear advantage.}) 18... Rxc3 (
18... Qf6 {threatening a discovered attack with Bh2+ would have kept Black in
the game.} 19. Bb2 Bh2+ 20. Kg2 Qxf3+ 21. Kxf3 Rxh3+ $14 {when Black has at
the very least restored material equality.}) 19. Bb2 {Black should have
retreated the rook to c7 but instead he played.} Rc6 {which is a big mistake
as now} 20. d5 {comes with tempo.} exd5 21. Rad1 {Black's position was already
difficult.} ({Stronger was} 21. Qxd5 $1 {with the idea Nf5 to target the g7
pawn and if} Bxe3 22. fxe3 Qe8 23. Rf3 $16 {followed by Raf1 puts Black under
serious pressure.}) 21... Nb6 {makes White's task even easier. Black's
position simply collapses after} 22. Nxd5 Nxd5 23. Rxd5 Qe7 24. Ba3 {Black
must have missed this strong tactic, taking advantage of Black's weak back
rank.} Qxa3 25. Rd8+ Ke7 26. Rxh8 {White has just won an exchange and had no
trouble closing out the game.} Qb4 27. Rd1 Re6 28. a3 Qb6 29. Qd5 g6 30. Rh7
Kf6 31. h4 {Black resigned. 1-0 Gumularz, Szymon (2458)-Marosi, Leven (2288)
29th EU Open U18 Riga 2018} 1-0

