46,40,224,39,181,66,66,66,210,120,29995,29996,29997,29998] The following is a
model game in the 3...Bg4 4...Bxf3 variation between super-GM MVL and GM
Evgenij Agrest from Sweden from the 2017 Rapid PRO Chess League.} 1. e4 c6 2.
Nf3 d5 3. Nc3 Bg4 4. h3 Bxf3 5. Qxf3 Nf6 6. Be2 {MVL's favorite move and my
recommendation in chapter 7.} e6 7. O-O Nbd7 8. d4 dxe4 9. Nxe4 Nxe4 10. Qxe4
Nf6 11. Qd3 Bd6 {This was all covered in the 7...dxe4 variation in chapter 7.
There I mentioned that even though Black is quite solid and without any
apparent weaknesses, White's position is much easier to play since he has more
space and the pair of bishops. The following is a masterclass on how to win
these types of positions, which occur quite frequently in this course.} 12. a4
{White starts by gaining space on the queenside, intending to follow up with
a4-a5.} Qe7 13. a5 a6 14. Rd1 {The way to play these positions where your
opponent has no active plan is to first make small incremental improvements
and then have a look around. While there isn't an obvious way to crack Black's
position, White will apply a longstanding amount of pressure which is very
hard to sustain in a practical game.} Rd8 15. Qf3 {White starts by improving
the position of his queen. From f3, the queen controls the e4 square and eyes
the b7-pawn, making Black think twice about breaking in the center with c7-c5.}
h6 16. g3 {White's light-squared bishop is unopposed and so MVL places all of
his pawns on dark-squares which will further restrict Black's dark-squared
bishop.} O-O 17. c3 {White reinforces the d4-pawn and prepares to gain even
more space with b2-b4.} Rd7 18. Kg2 {White improves the position of his king
and introduces the idea of expanding on the kingside with h4-h5 and possibly
even starting a kingside attack with Rh1 and g2-g5.} Rfd8 19. Re1 Bc7 20. b4 {
White now has complete control over the queenside.} Re8 21. Bd3 {Now it's time
to improve the position of the light-squared bishop, followed by bringing the
rook on a1 into the game and doubling on the e-file.} Qd8 22. Bc2 Bb8 23. Re2
Nd5 24. Bd2 {Clearing the way for Rae1. You might be asking, why is White
doubling on the e-file. Well, why not? It improves the position of the rook on
a1 and passes the move onto Black, who has no active plan and has already
improved his position to the max.} Nf6 25. Rae1 Rf8 26. Bc1 {Another
micro-improvement, White removes the bishop from the d-file. Was this
necessary? No, not really but this way this avoids any ...e5 breaks that take
advantage of the fact that the bishop is only defended by the rook.} Bc7 27. h4
{Having improved his position to the max and established full control of the
queenside, White now switches his attention to the kingside.} Bb8 28. Rh1 Nd5
29. Qd3 {Threatening checkmate in one with Qh7.} Nf6 30. g4 {And now White
launches a decisive attack. The fact that Black has less space means it's very
hard for him to bring enough defenders to the kingside for example, his bishop
on b8 can't really join the defense. Normally, Black would react to such flank
attacks by breaking in the center or alternatively drumming up counterplay on
the queenside. However, White completely neutralized any of these options
before starting a kingside attack.} e5 {Black desperately tries to create some
play in the center but it doesn't work.} 31. g5 e4 32. Qh3 Nd5 33. Rxe4 {
There goes the e-pawn. White is now a pawn up and his attack is still going
strong.} h5 34. Rhe1 {The e-file has opened up so it makes sense to double
rooks.} Re7 35. Rxe7 Nxe7 36. f4 {Here comes Freddy. Notice how all of White's
pawns are on dark-squares, completely restricting Black's bishop on b8 and
increasing the scope of White's light-squared bishop.} Nd5 37. Qf3 g6 38. Bd2 (
38. f5 $1 {would have finished Black right away.}) 38... Qd6 39. Re4 Ne7 40.
Re2 Nd5 41. f5 {White decides to break with f5 but this gives Black some
counterplay with Qh2+, which was completely unnecessary.} ({Better was to
first improve the position of the light-squared bishop with} 41. Bd3 $1) 41...
Qh2+ 42. Kf1 Qxh4 43. Bb3 {White goes after the knight on d5.} gxf5 44. Bxd5
cxd5 45. Qxd5 Bg3 46. g6 {Bh6 is now a big threat.} Qh3+ 47. Qg2 Qg4 ({This is
a big mistake. but not because of Exchanging queens with} 47... Qxg2+ {would
have kept the balance. A sample continuation is} 48. Kxg2 h4 49. Be1 Bxe1 50.
gxf7+ Kxf7 51. Rxe1 Rc8 52. Re3 Kf6 {when Black should be able to hold.}) 48.
Qxb7 (48. Bh6 {would have won the game on the spot.} Rb8 49. gxf7+ Kxf7 50.
Qd5+ $18 {is lights out.}) 48... f4 49. gxf7+ Rxf7 50. Qd5 Qh3+ 51. Kg1 f3 {
And Black blunders mate in three. This was a rapid game so both players were
probably quite low on time.} 52. Re8+ Kg7 53. Qg5+ {Black resigned since he
was about to get mated with Qh6. Apart from allowing shenanigans with ...Qh2+,
White was full in full control over the rest of the game. This game is a great
illustration of how White can make the most of out of his bishop pair and
space advantages, and slowly dismantle Black's position with incremental
improvements. 1-0 (53) Vachier Lagrave, M (2803)-Agrest, E (2593) PRO League
2017} 1-0

[Event "FIDE Grand Prix Riga"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "2019.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Vachier Lagrave , Maxime"]
[Black "Navara, David"]
[Result "1-0"]
[ECO "B11"]
[WhiteElo "2775"]
[BlackElo "2734"]
[PlyCount "37"]

{[%evp 0,37,29,18,77,38,44,38,68,43,46,34,51,23,23,7,71,69,66,18,36,37,30,37,
37,75,83,61,88,67,117,106,160,171,225,231,225,231,219,219] This is a model
game in the 3...Bg4 4...Bxf3 variation with ...Nf6 between two super GMs, MVL
with the White pieces and Navara with Black.} 1. e4 c6 2. Nf3 d5 3. Nc3 Bg4 4.
h3 Bxf3 5. Qxf3 Nf6 6. Be2 {This is MVL's favorite move and the one I
recommended in chapter 7.} e6 7. O-O {White is now threatening to expand in
the center with d2-d4.} Bc5 {Black develops dark-squared bishop and prevents
d2-d4.} 8. Rd1 {Renewing the threat of d2-d4.} Bd4 9. Qf4 {A very strong move,
threatening e4-e5.} e5 {As I mentioned in chapter 7, specifically in the7...
Bc5 variation, this move is a big mistake.} (9... Bxc3 {is Black's only
sensible continuation.}) 10. Qg3 {White retreats the queen and attacks the g7
pawn. We now see the point behind Qf4, by provoking ...e5 the bishop on d4 is
cut off from the defense of the g7 pawn.} dxe4 11. d3 {A very strong move,
prying open the d-file taking advantage of the fact that our rook on d1
opposes Black's queen on d8. Black is already in big trouble.} exd3 12. Bxd3
Nbd7 ({As mentioned in the theoretical part of the course} 12... O-O {is
strongly met by} 13. Ne2 $16 {when Black has no good way of meeting the threat
of c2-c3, picking up the dark-squared bishop. If the bishop moves away, the
discovery with Bxh7+ will pick up Black's queen.}) 13. Ne2 {This is inaccurate.
Navara misses a big chance to equalize and instead blunders with} ({Better was
} 13. Qxg7 Rg8 14. Qh6 {when White is close to winning. The point is that after
} Bxc3 15. bxc3 e4 {is strongly met by} 16. Qh4 {when} exd3 {loses on the spot
to} 17. Re1+ Kf8 18. Bh6+ Rg7 19. Qg5 $18 {with a completely winning position.}
) 13... O-O ({Black should have simply retreated with} 13... Bb6 {when White's
knight on e2 is completely misplaced. Note that} 14. Qxg7 {now does not yield
White an advantage because after} Rg8 15. Qh6 e4 $11 {White no longer has Qh4
followed by Re1 because the knight on e2 is blocking the e-file.}) 14. Bf5 {
Now Black has big problems along the d-file. Furthermore, Bh6 is also a
serious threat. In fact, White is close to winning.} Nc5 15. Bh6 {Threatening
Qxg7#.} Nh5 (15... Ne6 {fails to save Black} 16. Bxe6 Nh5 17. Qg4 fxe6 18.
Qxe6+ Kh8 19. Be3 Qc7 20. Nxd4 exd4 21. Rxd4 $18 {White is a pawn up and
Black's pieces are completely uncoordinated. White is winning.}) 16. Qg4 {
White moves his queen out of danger, now threatening Qxh5 as well as Nxd4.} Qd6
({Protecting the knight with} 16... g6 {loses to} 17. Nxd4 exd4 18. Bxf8 Qxf8
19. Rxd4 $18 {White is an exchange up with a completely winning position.}) 17.
Qxh5 Qxh6 18. Qxh6 gxh6 19. c3 {Black's bishop is trapped and so Navara
resigned. What a miniature, it's not every day you see a super GM go down in
less than 20 moves! 1-0 Vachier Lagrave, Maxime (2775)-Navara, David (2734)
FIDE Grand Prix Riga 2019} 1-0

[Event "Wch Rapid Moscow"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "2019.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Vachier Lagrave , Maxime "]
[Black "Mamedyarov, Shakhriyar"]
[Result "1-0"]
[ECO "B11"]
[WhiteElo "2780"]
[BlackElo "2772"]
[PlyCount "73"]

{[%evp 0,73,29,39,74,38,44,38,47,43,43,50,51,13,68,71,29,49,52,27,13,20,38,-15,
-3,-23,-40,24,21,65,67,80,72,98,71,71,70,70,64,35,50,49,78,47,73,73,116,53,119,
106,115,124,114,116,177,170,186,189,197,177,184,175,212,224,232,204,246,241,
241,235,241,211,243,236,225,224] The following is a model game in the 3...Bg4
4...Bxh3 variation between super GMs Maxime Vachier Lagrave and Shakhriyar
Mamedyarov from the 2019 World Rapid Championship.} 1. e4 c6 2. Nf3 d5 3. Nc3
Bg4 4. h3 Bxf3 5. Qxf3 e6 6. Be2 Bc5 7. O-O Nf6 8. Rd1 Bd4 9. Qf4 {A very
strong move. White is threatening e4-e5. MVL sacrifices the e4-pawn but his
lead in development together with the bishop pair will give him a big
initiative.} Bxc3 {Mamedyarov correctly accepts White's sacrifice.} 10. bxc3
Nxe4 11. Ba3 {White stops Black from castling short.} Nd7 12. Rab1 {Bringing
the rook into the game with a tempo on the b7 pawn.} Qa5 {This is Black's best
move, counterattacking our bishop. This was all covered in the 7...Bc5
variation in chapter 7, where I recommended the novel 13.Rb3. This move is
stronger than MVL's choice of} 13. Bb4 {Nevertheless, Black is still under
some pressure after 13.Bb4.} Qd8 {This retreating move is a big mistake and
allows White to gain a big advantage.} (13... Qc7 {holds without too many
problems and is the reason why I recommended the novel 13.Rb3N.}) 14. c4 {
A very strong break. White is now threatening cxd5 followed by c2-c4 after
which Black's central construction would collapse.} c5 15. cxd5 {A strong
intermediate move, taking advantage of the fact that the knight on e4 is
unprotected.} exd5 16. Bc3 {with a double-attack on the g7 and b7 pawns.} O-O
17. Rxb7 Nxc3 18. dxc3 {White has restored material equality and is clearly
better. In such an open position, White's light-squared bishop is much
stronger than Black's knight. Furthermore, White's pieces are much more active
notably the rook on b7 and the pawn on d5 is a big target.} Nf6 19. Bf3 {
A natural move, but White had an even better option.} (19. c4 $1 {was even
stronger, exploiting the pin along the d-file.} Qe8 20. Qf3 dxc4 21. Bxc4 $18 {
White is threatening Rxf7+ and Rc7. Black is busted.}) 19... Qa5 20. c4 Qa4 (
20... dxc4 {loses to} 21. Rxf7 Rxf7 22. Bxa8 $18 {when Black's bank rank is
very weak and his king is just too exposed.}) 21. Rc7 {Going after the c5 pawn.
} Rab8 22. Rxc5 Rb4 23. c3 Rb2 ({The alternative} 23... Rxc4 24. Rxc4 dxc4 25.
Rd2 $18 {isn't much better than the text. White can expand on the kingside
with g2-g4-g5 and then pick up the c4 pawn with Bd5.}) 24. Qd4 dxc4 25. Rxc4
Qc2 26. a4 {White is a clean pawn up and had no trouble closing out the game.}
a5 27. Rc5 {The a5-pawn is also about to drop.} h6 28. Rxa5 Re8 29. Ra8 {
Simple chess, it makes sense to exchange a pair of rooks to limit Black's
counterplay.} Rxa8 30. Bxa8 Ra2 31. Bc6 {Covering the a4-pawn.} g6 32. Re1 Kg7
33. c4 Ra3 34. Bb5 Rd3 35. Qe5 {Pinning Black's knight, which won't be able to
move for the rest of the game.} Rd2 36. Rf1 Re2 37. Qa1 {Black has no way of
stopping White's a-pawn, which will simply march down the board. Black had
seen enough and decided to throw in the towel. 1-0 Vachier Lagrave, Maxime 
(2780)-Mamedyarov, Shakhriyar (2772) Wch Rapid Moscow 2019} 1-0

