[FEN "r4rk1/p1bnnppp/2p1p3/q2pP3/3P4/B1N2Q1P/P1P1BPP1/1R3RK1 b - - 0 16"]
[PlyCount "8"]

16... c5 {GM Alexey Dreev with the Black pieces has just ...c7-c5. Can you
spot what's wrong with this typical pawn break?} 17. Rb5 {Immediately
exploiting the drawback of Black's last move, which lost control over the b5
and d5 squares.} Qxa3 18. Nxd5 {Uncorking a discovered attack on the queen and
hitting the knight on e7.} Qxf3 19. Nxe7+ {Check! This intermediate move
ensures White will end up with an extra pawn.} Kh8 20. Bxf3 {White was a pawn
up and went on to win in 1-0 Paravyan, David (2630)-Dreev, Alexey (2635) St
Petersburg 2018.} *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Thematic Tactics"]
[Black "Exercise 3"]
[Result "*"]
[SetUp "1"]
[FEN "rnbqkb1r/1p1n1ppp/p3p3/2ppP1N1/3P4/2NB4/PPP2PPP/R1BQ1RK1 b kq - 0 8"]
[PlyCount "10"]

8... cxd4 {Black has just snatched the pawn on d4 with ...cxd4. How did White
punish this greedy move?} 9. Nxe6 {A thematic sacrifice, opening up the e8-h5
diagonal.} fxe6 10. Qh5+ Ke7 11. Bg5+ Nf6 12. exf6+ Kd6 (12... gxf6 {loses to}
13. Bxf6+ Kxf6 14. Qh4+ $18 {which will pick up the queen on d8.}) 13. fxg7 {
White quickly won in 1-0 Fernandes, Julio (2015)-Van Riemsdijk, Dirk (2132)
Mogi das Cruzes 2013.} *

