10. Rd1 Ne5 {Black decided to ignore the attack on the queen on d5 and instead
counter-attack White's queen. Can you spot why this move is flawed?} 11. Qf4 {
Simple and strong. White removes the queen from danger and renews the threat
on Black's queen on d5.} Qa5 12. Nc5 {A very strong move, blocking the queen's
defense of the knight on e5.} Qc7 13. Nd7 {A fantastic shot! If you saw this
move from the starting position, give yourself a pat on the back! This is the
final piece of the combination. White exploits the fact that the queen on c7
is unprotected.} f6 14. Nxf8 Kxf8 15. Bc5+ Ke8 16. Bd6 {Bxe5 is coming next
with a decisive advantage. Black's king was stuck in the middle of the board
and White went on to win in 1-0 (46) Lu, Shanglei (2546)-Dreev, Alexey (2667)
Dubai 2014.} *

